<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-314-690  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 314 690.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Design  June 1 1989 v28 n11 p78(9).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Negotiating the obstacles to building military computers.andO;(includes related articles on military needs, microcomputers,documentation and software development)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Lieberman, David.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Military recognition of the economic advantages of standardizationis creating opportunities for vendors of system-level componentsto enter the defense arena.andP;  The Department of Defense, afteryears of adhering to proprietary standards, now endorsescommercial off-the-shelf equipment (COTS).andP;  COTS hardware may notbe readily adaptable to military-specification demands, a pitfallwhich has affected some contractors and subcontractors.andP;  Militaryenvironments also demand different packaging habits thancommercial environments because of the need for high tolerances.andO;'Commercial-equivalent' hardware provides an alternative standardwhich takes military constraints into account.andP;  A completely newstandard consisting of commonality and consistency of procurementis ideal.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Defense ContractsComputer Systems IntegratorsSystem DesignBusesStandardsMilitaryUnited States. Department of Defense.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotographtable.andO;Caption:   Moesi state model. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>